8
00:03:53,967 --> 00:04:01,772
''save a fear tears,
a few sighs''

9
00:04:02,976 --> 00:04:06,776
l told you to keep the place tidy.

10
00:04:07,647 --> 00:04:12,778
lf that manuscript was here,
then where has it got to ?

11
00:04:15,321 --> 00:04:18,950
- What do you know, then?
- He wished you good morning.

12
00:04:19,158 --> 00:04:21,956
Fool!
l mean about the manuscript!

13
00:04:22,996 --> 00:04:24,964
You've looked at my things?

14
00:04:26,833 --> 00:04:28,300
Wings?

15
00:04:29,168 --> 00:04:32,797
This is a newspaper office,
not a bird house!

16
00:04:33,006 --> 00:04:34,473
Wings, indeed!

17
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:39,475
Things.
Have you read the poems l left?

18
00:04:40,013 --> 00:04:41,139
l have.

19
00:04:41,514 --> 00:04:44,483
Did you like them?
You'll publish them?

20
00:04:44,684 --> 00:04:47,312
l haven't lost my mind.

21
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:51,820
Call that gibberish poetry? lt's
a crusade against unemployment.

22
00:04:52,692 --> 00:04:59,097
Poetry deals with delicacies:
You must write poems about love.

23
00:04:59,632 --> 00:05:01,600
You are incomparable, Sir!

24
00:05:02,135 --> 00:05:04,433
Write about intoxication...

25
00:05:04,971 --> 00:05:10,273
...the beauty of a cup,
or a fine woman.

26
00:05:10,476 --> 00:05:13,604
Shut up.
You don't write poetry.

27
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:16,778
Have you read poets
like Mir and Momin?

28
00:05:17,650 --> 00:05:21,609
Yes, and Josh and Faiz, who are
beyond your comprehension.

29
00:05:22,155 --> 00:05:25,454
Give me my poems.
- We will find them later.

30
00:05:30,163 --> 00:05:36,796
What do you think
you're doing young man?

31
00:05:43,176 --> 00:05:47,806
What right have you
to throw away my poems?

32
00:05:48,014 --> 00:05:50,812
Should l make a paper hat of them?

33
00:05:51,017 --> 00:05:54,748
Don't insult them by
wearing them on a hollow head.

34
00:05:54,954 --> 00:05:56,922
My head? Hollow?

35
00:05:58,124 --> 00:06:02,254
How about yours? lf you're
a poet, l'm a donkey!

36
00:06:03,629 --> 00:06:06,757
lt's clear, and it's nice
to hear you admit it.

37
00:06:19,979 --> 00:06:23,278
Are you weighing
vegetables or gold?

38
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:29,288
There's Uncle Vijay!

39
00:06:53,346 --> 00:06:55,246
l've caught him.

40
00:07:05,124 --> 00:07:10,084
l'm not your enemy.
Why run from your mother?

41
00:07:10,963 --> 00:07:17,266
Where have you been?
l can't bear to see your suffer.

42
00:07:18,137 --> 00:07:19,434
l'm well, mother.

43
00:07:19,639 --> 00:07:24,269
Sure you are. Just look
at the state you're in.

44
00:07:25,311 --> 00:07:32,774
Come home. l've hidden away
some good food for you.

45
00:07:33,319 --> 00:07:36,948
You've found him?
- Yes.

46
00:07:54,273 --> 00:07:57,242
Well, mother.
So your poet is home!

47
00:07:59,612 --> 00:08:02,581
Every literate fool thinks
he's poet.

48
00:08:05,017 --> 00:08:08,077
Where else can he get food
as a parasite?

49
00:08:08,287 --> 00:08:10,755
Take no notice of them. Eat.

50
00:08:15,995 --> 00:08:21,934
See? We earn and mother feeds
delicacies to her layabout.

51
00:08:22,301 --> 00:08:24,769
He's shameless.

52
00:08:25,471 --> 00:08:30,602
lf he had any self-respect, he'd
starve rather than eat here.

53
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:39,941
Shut up, you two! l won't hear
a word said against him.

54
00:08:40,486 --> 00:08:45,617
He's back after so long, and
you can't bear to see him eat.

55
00:08:45,825 --> 00:08:50,455
He's hale and hearty. Why doesn't
he earn and not burden us?

56
00:08:50,997 --> 00:08:55,457
After his father died,
you should look after him.

57
00:08:56,002 --> 00:09:02,305
lt wasn't our wish that our
parents produce such a layabout.

58
00:09:07,179 --> 00:09:09,477
That l must have to hear this!

59
00:09:10,516 --> 00:09:13,815
lt was my misfortunate
to give birth to you two.

60
00:09:14,353 --> 00:09:17,811
You won't even let me work,
because of your ''prestige''.

61
00:09:20,293 --> 00:09:23,490
lf l could work as a maid,
l could feed my son.

62
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:29,994
Sister-in-law,
Where are my poems?

63
00:09:30,536 --> 00:09:33,334
Address me, not the women.

64
00:09:33,773 --> 00:09:36,003
l sold them for
10 annas as waste paper.

65
00:09:44,050 --> 00:09:50,512
Waste paper?
You sold my poems for ten annas?

66
00:09:53,225 --> 00:09:55,284
Uncouth fools no better.

67
00:09:55,661 --> 00:10:03,124
You call me uncouth?
Did you hear that, brother?

68
00:10:03,336 --> 00:10:10,469
l got rid of them this morning.
Now l'll get rid of you! Out!

69
00:10:15,514 --> 00:10:20,645
Where will you go on an empty
stomach? Who will tend to you?

70
00:10:22,021 --> 00:10:23,648
You take me along with you.

71
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:27,485
l don't want to stay here
for another minute.

72
00:10:28,694 --> 00:10:32,323
Don't worry, mother.
l'll do my best.

73
00:10:34,033 --> 00:10:38,333
l'll take you away from here
as soon as l can.

74
00:10:51,050 --> 00:10:55,612
Let me get on with my work
instead of searching waste paper.

75
00:10:56,155 --> 00:10:59,124
But there was an important file.

76
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:01,790
A file?
Containing handwritten papers?

77
00:11:02,828 --> 00:11:06,457
Where are they?
- A woman bought them.

78
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:13,970
They caught her eye, she read
some, then she took them away.

79
00:11:14,507 --> 00:11:16,475
Which woman?
Where does she live?

80
00:11:16,676 --> 00:11:19,645
l don't know;
she wasn't a local person.

81
00:11:28,354 --> 00:11:30,982
lf she comes again, l'll ask.

82
00:11:42,702 --> 00:11:44,329
Come come!

83
00:11:45,037 --> 00:11:47,005
Have you fallen out with your
brothers again?

84
